SIMPLE: worse
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Worse
<hw>Worse</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>, <pos>compar.</pos> of
<er>Bad</er>. <ety>[OE. <ets>werse</ets>, <ets>worse</ets>,
<ets>wurse</ets>, AS. <ets>wiersa</ets>, <ets>wyrsa</ets>, a comparative
with no corresponding positive; akin to OS. <ets>wirsa</ets>, OFries.
<ets>wirra</ets>, OHG. <ets>wirsiro</ets>, Icel. <ets>verri</ets>, Sw.
<ets>v⟦aum⟧rre</ets>, Dan. <ets>v⟦aum⟧rre</ets>, Goth.
<ets>wa⟦iacute⟧rsiza</ets>, and probably to OHG. <ets>werran</ets> to
bring into confusion, E. <ets>war</ets>, and L. <ets>verrere</ets> to
sweep, sweep along. As <ets>bad</ets> has no comparative and
superlative, <ets>worse</ets> and <ets>worst</ets> are used in lieu of
them, although etymologically they have no relation to
<ets>bad</ets>.]</ety> <def>Bad, ill, evil, or corrupt, in a greater
degree; more bad or evil; less good; specifically, in poorer health;
more sick; -- used both in a physical and moral sense.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Or <qex>worse</qex>, if men <qex>worse</qex> can devise.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[She] was nothing bettered, but rather grew <qex>worse</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Mark v. 26.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Evil men and seducers shall wax <qex>worse</qex> and
<qex>worse</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>2 Tim. iii. 13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There are men who seem to believe they are not bad while another
can be found <qex>worse</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Rambler.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>⟦ldquo⟧But I love him.⟦rdquo⟧ ⟦ldquo⟧Love him? <qex>Worse</qex>
and <qex>worse</qex>.⟦rdquo⟧</q> <rj><qau>Gay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Worse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Worse
<hw>Worse</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Loss; disadvantage;
defeat.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Judah was put to the <xex>worse</xex> before
Israel.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Kings xiv. 12.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is worse; something less good; <as>as,
think not the <ex>worse</ex> of him for his enterprise</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Worse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Worse
<hw>Worse</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>wiers</ets>,
<ets>wyrs</ets>; akin to OS. & OHG. <ets>wirs</ets>, Icel.
<ets>verr</ets>, Goth, <ets>wa⟦iacute⟧rs</ets>; a comparative adverb
with no corresponding positive. See <er>Worse</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety>
<def>In a worse degree; in a manner more evil or bad.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now will we deal <qex>worse</qex> with thee than with them.</q>
<rj><qau>Gen. xix. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Worse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Worse
<hw>Worse</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>wursien</ets>, AS.
<ets>wyrsian</ets> to become worse.]</ety> <def>To make worse; to put
disadvantage; to discomfit; to worst. See <er>Worst</er>,
<pos>v.</pos></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Weapons more violent, when next we meet,⟦br⟧
May serve to better us and <qex>worse</qex> our foes.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Worsen</ent>⟦br⟧
